http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: North Dakota Physical Education Content Standards

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The North Dakota Physical Education Content and Achievement Standards were written to provide physical education teachers and school districts with a guide for quality physical education programs. Physical education and wellness are evolving to provide a more comprehensive lifestyle management approach, encouraging physical fitness and activity, sound nutritional practices, and assessment through the use of the latest technology.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/rightsHolder.value: North Dakota Department of Public Instruction

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Standard 1: Movement Forms
Students demonstrate motor skills and movement patterns needed to perform a variety of physical activities.
Movement Skills
Demonstrate walking as a basic locomotor skill (i.e., in a straight line with correct body alignment)
Demonstrate the underhand ball roll as a basic object control skill (i.e., back swing and follow through, lower body, opposition)
Demonstrate a variety of basic non-locomotor skills (e.g., bending, twisting, turning, lifting, body shapes)
Demonstrate galloping and hopping as basic locomotor skills (i.e., forward movement, step together step, hop on right foot, hop on left foot)
Demonstrate a variety of basic non-locomotor skills (e.g., raising and lowering body parts, rocking and swaying, swinging, pushing and pulling)
Demonstrate the underhand throw as a basic object control skill (i.e., swing arm back, step with opposition, and follow through)
Demonstrate the horizontal and vertical jump as basic locomotor skills (e.g., jumps a distance using floor markings, jumps for height using mats)
Use basic object control skills (e.g., chest pass, bouncing a ball, tossing a bean bag)
Demonstrate mature form in running (i.e., moment of non-support, arm alignment, opposition)
Demonstrate mature form in sliding (i.e., moment of non-support, not crossing legs)
Demonstrate mature form in skipping (i.e., alternating hops, opposition in upper body, rhythm)
Use locomotor skills to complete a task (e.g., moving in pathways, right/left directions)
Demonstrate mature form in leaping (i.e., momentary balance on right and left foot)
Use mature form in non-locomotor skills (e.g., strike a suspended ball, kick a stationary ball)
Combine non-locomotor skills in a sequence (e.g., tuck and straddle, bend and squat)
Demonstrate mature form in object control skills (e.g., dribbling a soccer ball)
Demonstrate object control skills to complete a task (e.g., throwing, catching)
Demonstrate the combination of locomotor, non-locomotor, and object control skills in modified team or individual sports (e.g., trapping and dribbling in soccer)
Demonstrate a variety of rhythmic movements (e.g., square dance, line dance, folk dance, jump rope routines)
Demonstrate movement patterns (e.g., screening in basketball, move to the open space) in modified team and individual activities
Apply intermediate skills in physical activities (e.g., arm strokes in swimming, balance in dance, arm swing in serving)
Apply advanced skills in physical activities (e.g., arm and leg strokes in swimming, balance and change in levels in dance, arm swing and footwork in serving)
Apply combination movement skills (e.g., high and low movement with a turn, jump, shoot) in a variety of lifetime activities (e.g., dance, outdoor pursuits, tennis)
Control in Movement
Use proper body control while moving through personal and general space
Use control in travel activities (e.g., changes directions in a safe manner, shows an awareness of objects and other people when moving)
Use control in travel activities at various speeds (e.g., shows an awareness of objects and other people when moving)
Demonstrate static balance (e.g., stand on one foot, balancing on an object)
Use control in static and dynamic balance activities (e.g., using balance board, walking on a balance beam)
Use space to move safely in different directions at various speeds (e.g., decreasing space as you increase speed)
Adapt a skill to the demands of the environment (e.g., stopping, passing, kicking, striking, throwing, catching, bounce or chest pass)
Standard 2: Movement Concepts
Students understand and apply movement concepts, principles, strategies, and tactics to learn and perform physical activities.
Movement Concepts
Respond to visual, verbal/auditory cues (i.e., starting and stopping on a signal)
Identify body parts (e.g., head, shoulders, chest, elbows, hands, knees, feet)
Demonstrate the patterns of over, under, around, and through with the use of various equipment. (e.g., mini hurdles, cones and hoop stands)
Identify basic body planes (e.g., front, back, side)
Demonstrate the patterns of left/right, forward/backward, and zigzag to verbal/auditory cues (e.g., "Weave through cones")

Demonstrate the basic sequence (e.g., standing in ready position, arm/leg preparation, making a target with your hands and stepping in opposition, and follow through) for kicking, throwing, and catching skills
Demonstrate basic movement concepts and strategies (e.g., force on surface or object, balance and twist, mimic/mirror)
Apply basic offensive/defensive strategies (e.g., marking and guarding, keep away) in pairs and small groups
Apply basic offensive/defensive strategies (e.g., screening, movement away from the ball) in physical activities and games in small and large groups
Apply offensive and defensive strategies (e.g., home base, ready position, strategies for singles vs. doubles) in a variety of modified team and individual sports
Identify biomechanical concepts (e.g., range of motion, angle of contact, leverage, force, speed, center of gravity) that govern different types of movement

Explain intermediate biomechanical concepts that govern different types of movement (e.g., how friction of different surfaces affects movement, how angle of launch affects trajectory and distance of a throw)
Apply intermediate biomechanical concepts that govern different types of movement (e.g., running on various surfaces, releasing a thrown object at different angles)

Explain advanced biomechanical concepts that govern different types of movement (e.g., how friction of different footwear and surfaces affects movement, how wind affects trajectory and distance of a thrown object)

Apply advanced biomechanical concepts that govern different types of movement (e.g., running with different footwear on various surfaces, releasing a thrown object into and with the wind at different angles)
Explain how complex biomechanical concepts govern different types of movement (e.g., factors that affect the distance of a thrown object)
Apply complex biomechanical concepts that govern different types of movement (e.g., throwing an object while running to avoid an obstacle)
Improving Performance
Explain why practice is important in learning motor skills and improving performance
Explain why feedback (from teacher and self) and practice are important in learning motor skills and improving performance
Describe the importance of practice and conditioning (e.g., practice throwing to increase accuracy) in improving the performance of motor skills
Demonstrate movement concepts (e.g., longer throw, weight transfer concepts) to refine movement skills
Apply self assessment to improve motor performance
Apply concepts (e.g., appropriate practice improves performance) that impact quality of movement
Apply teacher and peer feedback to improve motor performance
Provide feedback (e.g., verbal, nonverbal, and constructive) to others on a variety of motor skills to improve motor performance
Apply the principles of training and conditioning (e.g., using target heart rate zone to monitor intensity, warm up and cool down) to various activities
Identify the components of skill-related fitness (i.e., agility, balance, coordination, power, speed, reaction time)
Explain the skill-related components (i.e., agility, power, balance, coordination, reaction time, speed) that govern achievement, maintenance, and improvement of motor skills
Explain the psychological principles (e.g., positive self-talk, visualization, relaxation) that govern achievement, maintenance, and improvement of motor skills
Apply the skill-related components (i.e., agility, power, balance, coordination, reaction time, speed) that govern achievement, maintenance, and improvement of motor skills
Analyze movement patterns (e.g., golf swing, basketball free throw, dance) to improve performance
Apply the psychological principles (e.g., positive self-talk, visualization, relaxation) that govern achievement, maintenance, and improvement of motor skills
Analyze the psychological principles (e.g., stress, anger, visualization, self image) that affect physical activities
Standard 3: Physical Activity
Students participate in regular physical activity.
Benefits of Physical Activity
Identify the basic health benefits of regular physical activity (e.g., feel better, have more energy, get stronger, live longer)
Identify the health benefits of regular physical activity (e.g., strong heart, strong muscles, good flexibility)
Describe the health benefits of regular physical activity (e.g., exercising muscles makes them stronger)
Compare the types of physical activities that enhance health (e.g., bowling compared to cross country skiing, aerobic compared to leisure)
Identify the benefits of flexibility (e.g., increased range of motion)
Identify the benefits of cardio respiratory endurance (e.g., stronger heart, lower resting heart rate, quicker recovery)
Identify health benefits associated with muscular strength and endurance (e.g., increase stamina, increase power)
Identify health benefits (e.g., disease prevention) and risks (e.g., obesity) associated with the effect of physical activity on body composition
Identify relationships between physical activity and effects on the body (e.g., reduce stress, social interaction, increased energy)
Explain the long-term physiological benefits (e.g., increased energy, improved health related fitness, disease prevention) of physical activity
Explain the long-term psychological (e.g., healthy self-image, improved confidence, stress reduction) benefits of physical activity
Analyze long-term physiological benefits (e.g., weight management, blood pressure regulation) of regular participation in physical activity
Evaluate lifelong outcomes (e.g., life expectancy, healthcare costs, disease prevention) of regular participation in physical activities
Participates in Physical Activity
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., playing hard, running) before and after school, during recess, and during the school day
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., be active with family members and friends) before and after school, during recess, and during the school day
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., riding bike, running and playing outside) before and after school, during recess, and during school day
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., free play, play with peers, organized activity)
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., free play, play with peers, organized activity)
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., free play, play with peers, organized activity)
Participate regularly in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., during school day, before and after school, organized outside school activity)
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., during school day, before and after school, organized outside school activity)
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., during school day, before and after school, organized outside of school activity)
Participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity (e.g., during the school day, before and after school, organized outside school activity)
Evaluate personal participation in physical activity in and out of school using various methods of documentation (e.g., physical activity log, pedometer steps)
Participate in student-initiated physical activity both in and out of school (e.g., intramural and interscholastic sports, parks and recreation leagues, health clubs, walking and biking)
Implement a personal physical activity program based on a personal health and physical assessment
Opportunities for Physical Activity
Identify opportunities for physical activity within the school setting (e.g., intramural and interscholastic sports)
Identify opportunities for physical activity in the community (e.g., sports, parks and recreation leagues, health clubs, walking and biking paths)
Explain a variety of factors (e.g., cost of activity, available facilities, required equipment, required time, physical limitations) that impact participation in physical activity.
Describe how factors (e.g., age, gender, cultural background, socioeconomic status) affect physical activity choices and physical activity patterns throughout one's life.
Standard 4: Fitness Concepts
Students understand and apply fitness concepts to achieve and maintain a health-enhancing level of physical fitness.
Physiological Response to Physical Activity
Identify the body's response to physical activity (e.g., red face, sweating, increased thirst, increased breathing)
Identify activities that develop flexibility (e.g., stretching toward the toes while in the sit-and reach position, moving joints through full range of motion)
Explain ways the body responds to physical activity (e.g., sweating, increased heart rate, increased breathing)
Demonstrate activities that develop muscular strength and endurance (e.g., climbing, weight bearing)
Describe immediate physiological responses to various flexibility activities (e.g., greater range of motion, discomfort with unsafe stretches)
Identify immediate and long term physiological responses (e.g., shortness of breath, increased heart rate, burning calories) to various cardio respiratory activities
Identify immediate physiological responses to muscular strength and endurance activities (e.g., muscular fatigue, muscular discomfort)
Demonstrate ways to monitor the body's response to physical activity (e.g., checking pulse with fingers, using a heart rate monitor)
Analyze the body's physiological response to various types of exercise or activity (e.g., maintaining target heart rate zone in a variety of activities)
Analyze the body's physiological response to caloric consumption and expenditure
Fitness-Related Components and Goals
Identify strengths and areas of need based upon fitness assessments (e.g., compare criterion-reference standards to personal performance)
Identify the health related components of fitness (i.e., cardio respiratory endurance, flexibility, body composition, muscular strength and endurance)
Apply fitness assessments to set a fitness goal (e.g., show improvement in one or more health related components of fitness)

Describe the relationship between regular participation in physical activity and physical fitness (e.g., how different levels of activity can affect physical fitness, using the Fitness Education Pyramid)
Set goals related to personal fitness assessments (e.g., use the results of fitness assessment to set specific goals, such as increasing the number of sit-ups completed in one minute)
Identify physical activities (e.g., swimming, jogging for cardio respiratory fitness) for the development and maintenance of each component of health-related fitness
Identify physical activities that enhance each component of health-related fitness (e.g., swimming and jogging for cardio respiratory fitness)
Interpret the results of a physical fitness assessment to establish personal fitness goals
Explain the physiological principles (e.g., overload, progression, specificity, FITT) that govern achievement and maintenance of health-related fitness goals
Apply the physiological principles (e.g., overload, progression, specificity, FITT) that govern achievement and maintenance of personal health-related fitness goals
Design a personal fitness program based on the results of a physical fitness assessment, incorporating the physiological principles of training (e.g., overload, progression, specificity, FITT)
Assessment of Physical Fitness
Interpret recorded health-related physical fitness data for maintaining or improving levels of fitness
Analyze personal fitness data and compare scores to physiological changes over time (e.g., height, weight, age)
Evaluate personal health-related components of physical fitness (e.g., Pacer, Modified Sit & Reach, Harvard Step Test)
Life-Long Health
Describe a physically active lifestyle across a lifespan (e.g., active lifestyle timeline, survey a relative about activity habits)

Analyze the relationship between daily lifestyle choices and lifelong health (e.g., body composition-diabetes, heart disease-CPR/ First Aid training; muscle strength-low back pain, proper nutritional practices, drug awareness)

Describe opportunities for physical activities (e.g., fitness centers, golf courses, ski resorts, health fairs) and educational resources (e.g., dining nutritional guidelines, health brochures) available for maintaining a healthy and active lifestyle throughout adulthood
Achieving Physical Fitness
Compare physical fitness activities for their health enhancing potential and benefits

Analyze various methods (e.g., personal logs, data collection, self assessments) for monitoring activity levels to meet personal physical fitness needs (e.g., gaining weight, losing weight, increasing flexibility)
Maintenance of Physical Fitness
Adjust activity levels to meet personal fitness needs (e.g., monitor target heart rate or rate of perceived exertion and adjust level of intensity as appropriate)
Apply strategies to monitor and adjust activity levels to meet personal fitness needs (e.g., monitor target heart rate or rate of perceived exertion and adjust level of intensity as appropriate)
Standard 5: Behavior in Physical Activity
Students exhibit responsible personal and social behavior in physical activity settings.
Procedures and Personal Responsibility
Apply rules and procedures, (e.g., safety, equipment, directions) with teacher reinforcement, during physical activities
Apply rules and procedures during physical activities (e.g., safety, equipment, directions)
Identify reasons for rules and procedures during physical activities (e.g., safety, equipment, directions)
Demonstrate responsibility for their safe use of shared space (i.e., spatial awareness)
Accept responsibility for their actions during physical activities
Respect self, others, and equipment
Accept responsibility for their actions during physical activities without displaying negative reactions toward others
Demonstrate the ability to work independently on task until completed
Use safety precautions and procedures (e.g., safety gear, appropriate use of equipment, spotting techniques) in physical activity settings
Explain the importance of rules, procedures, and etiquette in physical activities (e.g., safety, fairness, organization, inclusion)
Demonstrate self-control (e.g., positive attitude, sportsmanship, etiquette) during physical activities
Identify potentially dangerous consequences of participation in physical activities (e.g., physical injury, dehydration, overheating, overuse)
Explain the potential for physical injury (e.g., potential dangers of high sticking) and property/equipment damage (e.g., misuse of equipment) while participating in physical activities or sports

Identify ethical decision-making, both independently and with others, in physical activity settings (e.g., respect for self and others, knowledge of rules, avoidance of inappropriate language, anger management, etiquette, fair play)
Explain procedures and safe practices for physical activity settings

Demonstrate ethical decision-making independently and with others in physical activity settings (e.g., respect for self and others, knowledge of rules, avoidance of inappropriate language, anger management, etiquette, fair play)
Demonstrate procedures and safe practices in all physical activity settings
Explain the impact of unethical decision making in physical activity settings (e.g., altercations, changing rules to level the playing field, suspensions)
Working with Others
Identify examples of respect for self and others (e.g., sharing space and equipment) during physical activities
Demonstrate respect for self and others (e.g., share space and equipment with others, show good sportsmanship)
Demonstrate respect for self and others (e.g., taking turns, sportsmanship, cooperation) during physical activities
Demonstrate cooperation and respect to others, in pairs, to achieve a common goal during physical activities
Identify appropriate communication skills (e.g., high five, compliment, non-threatening tone of voice) during physical education class
Demonstrate cooperation and respect to others, in small groups, to achieve a common goal during physical activities
Demonstrate appropriate communication skills, in pairs, during physical activities (e.g., listening to the needs of others, using appropriate tone of voice)
Demonstrate cooperation and respect to others, in large groups, to achieve a common goal during physical activities
Demonstrate appropriate communication skills during small group physical activities (e.g., listening to the needs of others, using appropriate tone of voice)
Demonstrate appropriate communication skills during large group physical activities (e.g., listening to the needs of others, using appropriate tone of voice)
Demonstrate appropriate conflict resolution skills (e.g., using "I" messages, allowing the right to agree and disagree)
Demonstrate respect for others (regardless of gender, ability level, physical or mental challenges, ethnic background, and socioeconomic status) during physical activities
Explain appropriate behaviors (e.g., teamwork, tolerance, respect, compassion) while participating in group settings to achieve a common goal
Apply appropriate behaviors (e.g., teamwork, tolerance, respect, compassion) while participating in group settings to achieve a common goal
Apply roles (e.g., leader and follower) to accomplish group goals in self- directed physical activities
